'''Howard Cecil Alloo''' (28 April 1895 &ndash; 23 October 1989) played [[first-class cricket]] for [[Otago cricket team|Otago]] in [[New Zealand]] from 1919 to 1929. His highest score was 62 against [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] in 1922-23.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/10/10691.html Otago v Wellington 1922-23]</ref>

His brothers [[Arthur Alloo|Arthur]] and [[Albert Alloo|Albert]] also played for Otago. The brothers were the grandsons of John Alloo, a Chinese-born businessman on the [[Ballarat]] goldfields, and his wife, n√©e Margaret Peacock, who had come out from Scotland. John and Margaret moved to the [[Otago Gold Rush|Otago goldfields]] in 1868, where he was employed by the Otago Police Force as a constable-interpreter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alloo |first1=Jenny |title=Dispersing Obscurity: The Alloo Family from Australia to New Zealand from 1868 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040607060219/http:/www.stevenyoung.co.nz:80/chinesevoice/ChinConf/S5.html#5.1%20Dispersing%20Obscurity:%20The%20Alloo%20Family%20From%20Australia%20to%20New%20Zealand%20from%201868 |accessdate=12 July 2019}}</ref>

In [[World War I]] Cecil Alloo served overseas in the Otago Infantry Battalion.<ref>[http://muse.aucklandmuseum.com/databases/Cenotaph/37335.detail?keywords=Alloo%20Howard%20Cecil%20World%20War%20I,%201914-1918 Cenotaph record, Howard Cecil Alloo] Retrieved 30 April 2014.</ref> Initially a sergeant, he was commissioned as a second lieutenant in mid-1918 and posted to C Company of the [[New Zealand Rifle Brigade (Earl of Liverpool's Own)|New Zealand Rifle Brigade]]. He was wounded in the [[Second Battle of Bapaume]] in August and invalided to England.<ref name=RP>{{cite web |last1=Palenski |first1=Ron |title=The story of a unique WW1 soldier |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/story-unique-ww1-soldier |website=Otago Daily Times |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>

He joined his brother Albert's law firm after the war, and later practised in [[Owaka]] and then in [[Timaru]]. He also served in the army during [[World War II]], this time in New Zealand.<ref name=RP/>

